== Cover versions ==
"The Climb" has been [[cover version|covered]] by several amateurs and established acts. Mirror Image Records' [[Independent music|indie rock]] group [[HelenaMaria]] covered the song and released it as a digital single in March 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amazon.com/dp/B0025TPE3M|title=Amazon.com: The Climb (Miley Cyrus Cover: HelenaMaria: MP3 Downloads|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]|accessdate=November 14, 2009}}</ref> Pop rock singer [[Kelly Clarkson]] with her backing singers Jill Pickering and Kate Rapier covered the song in a [[YouTube]] video published in September 2009. The three singers harmonized together in an intimate performance while Jill strummed an [[acoustic guitar]].<ref name="kccover">{{Cite web|url=http://www.accesshollywood.com/kelly-clarkson-covers-miley-cyrus-the-climb_article_23176|title=Kelly Clarkson Covers Miley Cyrus' 'The Climb'|date=September 19, 2009|work=[[Access Hollywood]]|publisher=[[NBC Universal Television Distribution]]|accessdate=November 14, 2009}}</ref> At auditions for the [[American Idol (season 9)|ninth season]] of the television singing competition ''[[American Idol]]'', "The Climb" was the most popular choice of song amongst contestants.<ref name="ewidol">{{cite web|url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2009/07/15/american-idol-auditions-miley-cyrus-climb/|title='American Idol': Miley Cyrus' 'The Climb' was the most popular audition song|first=Mandi|last=Bierly|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=July 15, 2009|publisher=Time Warner. Inc|accessdate=November 14, 2009}}</ref> Mandi Bierly, writing for ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', commented, "it sounds like we could get an Idol whose voice actually suits the inspirational tune that he or she will be forced to record as a first single. (Though the odds of that song being anywhere as good as 'The Climb'...)".<ref name="ewidol" /> While informing Cyrus of its popularity on ''American Idol'', the series' host [[Ryan Seacrest]] commented that the contestants "believe [it is] a song that will make an impression and [...] will get them into that next level".<ref name="onair">{{cite web|url=http://a1135.g.akamai.net/f/1135/18227/1h/cchannel.download.akamai.com/18227/podcast/LOSANGELES-CA/KIIS-FM/mileycyrus071609.mp3?CPROG=PCAST&MARKET=LOSANGELES-CA&NG_FORMAT=chrrhythmic&SITE_ID=842&STATION_ID=KIIS-FM&PCAST_AUTHOR=102.7_KIIS-FM&PCAST_CAT=morning_shows&PCAST_TITLE=On-Air_with_Ryan_Seacrest|title=On Air with Ryan Seacrest|work=[[On Air with Ryan Seacrest (radio)|On Air with Ryan Seacrest]]|publisher=[[Premiere Radio Networks]]|accessdate=November 14, 2009}}</ref> Cyrus replied,
{{quote|"Honestly, not to get all deep or anything, but that does, like, excite me so much because [...] that's what that show is all about: [...] following your dreams and not giving up [...] even though, like, that's what you're getting into, just to be judged, and pretty much to, like, be torn down, so just to build character, and I think that's so cool. That song could not be more appropriate for a better show [...] It's so cool, because that's, like, their one chance to make an impression and they chose my song, that's amazing."<ref name="onair" />}}
Kidz Bop Kids recorded a cover of the song for ''[[Kidz Bop 16]]''. Heather Phares of [[Allmusic]] commented, "The Kidz Bop Kids' version of Miley Cyrus' 'The Climb' sounds like an especially good elementary school choir performance".<ref>{{Cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r1612605|pure_url=yes}}|title=Kidz Bop 16 > Review|work=Allmusic|publisher=Rovi Corporation|accessdate=March 31, 2010}}</ref> Thia Megia, aged 14, performed a cover version of "The Climb" while competing in the semi-final of ''[[America's Got Talent]]''. Her performance was well received by the judges, with praise from [[Sharon Osbourne]] for her age-appropriate choice.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.zap2it.com/ithappenedlastnight/2009/08/americas-got-talent-arcadian-broad-is-footloose.html|title='America's Got Talent': Arcadian Broad is FOOTLOOSE!|first=Amanda|last=Reiher|work=[[Zap2it]]|date=August 4, 2009|publisher=[[Tribune Media Services]]|accessdate=November 14, 2009}}</ref> Australian singer [[Stan Walker]] performed the song as a contestant on the [[Australian Idol (season 7)|seventh season]] of ''[[Australian Idol]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com.au/news/0d2ff65c-stan-walker-new-oz-idol/|title=Perfect-Piped Performer Releases Album Details... Nov 22, 2009 Sarah-Louise James|date=November 22, 2009|accessdate=March 31, 2010|work=MTV News|publisher=Viacom|first=Sarah-Louise|last=James}}</ref> After winning the competition, he recorded the song for his debut album, ''[[Introducing... Stan Walker]]''. Jason Birchmeier of Allmusic said the cover turned out "well in large part because of Walker's vocal talents".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=10:g9fpxzesld6e~T1|title=Introducing... Stan Walker > Review|work=Allmusic|publisher=Rovi Coorporation|accessdate=March 30, 2010}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>  ''[[American Idol]]'' finalist Haeley Vaughn performed the song during the top twenty rounds of the ninth season.  The [[American Idol (season 10)|following season]], contestant [[Lauren Alaina]] performed the song during Idol Goes to the Movies week. The very [[American Idol (season 11)|next season]] Top 4 finalist [[Hollie Cavanagh]] performed the song to acclaim, earning herself her first standing ovation from the judges.  The song was covered by [[Lea Michele]], portraying [[Rachel Berry (Glee)|Rachel Berry]], in the 2010 ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'' episode "[[Laryngitis (Glee)|Laryngitis]]".<ref name="billboardcoverstory2">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/957988/miley-cyrus-the-billboard-cover-story|title=Miley Cyrus: The Billboard Cover Story|first=Ann|last=Donnahue|date=May 28, 2010|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc|accessdate=May 29, 2010|page=4}}</ref>  Filipino singer [[Charice]] has also done a live cover of this song.  Filipino acoustic singer Davey Langit also covered the song. The [[YouTube]]-founded [[R&B]] group, Ahmir also created a cover for the Climb, this cover is considered to be one of the best. The song was covered by [[Star Academy Middle East]] contestant [[Christine Saad<U+00E9>]] from [[Lebanon]] during the 10th week evaluation. Christine stated that the song was dedicated to her grandfather who died during the competition, but cried during her performance, which resulted to her being nominated for the [[Bottom 3]]. She was saved by the other candidate's votes with 7/11 of the voting process. Australian born singer Luke Cheung recorded a cover of the song for the 2010 album Life in Auto-Tune.

In 2012, it was performed and recorded by Vaj<U+00E8>n van den Bosch for the first season of Dutch talent show ''The Voice Kids'', a junior version of [[The Voice of Holland|The Voice]] of Holland.

The song has also been covered by the pop-rock band [[Amely (band)|Amely]]. It was recorded for the album of [[Punk Goes Pop|Punk Goes Pop 3]], but wasn't actually included on the compilation album of [[Fearless Records]]. Instead, another song of theirs was chosen for the bonus CD

''Brittany Miller ''covered Joe McElderry's version as the end credits of ''Jeanette Miller's Wedding Day''.

