=== Background and composition ===
In the same year of "The Climb"'s original release, British executive [[Simon Cowell]] chose for [[Joe McElderry]], [[Olly Murs]], and [[Stacey Solomon]], the three finalists of the [[The X Factor (UK Series 6)|sixth series]] of the British television talent contest ''[[The X Factor (UK)|The X Factor]]'', to record the song in preparation for a single release as soon as the winner was announced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mileycyrus.com/2009/12/03/simon-cowell-choses-the-climb-for-x-factor/|title=Simon Cowell choses 'The Climb' for X Factor|date=December 3, 2009|accessdate=December 3, 2009|work=MileyCyrus.com|publisher=[[Hollywood Records]]|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5lkyFayAs|archivedate=December 3, 2009}}</ref> After Solomon's elimination, Murs and McElderry sang the song on December 13, 2009, as their final performance in the competition. Upon winning the competition, McElderry's version of "The Climb", produced by [[Quiz & Larossi]], was released on December 14, 2009 by [[Syco Music]] as the first single from his album ''Wide Awake'' (2010).<ref name="dailymail">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-1235523/X-Factor-Favourite-Joe-McElderry-clinches-title.html|title=Joe McElderry wins The X Factor with 61% of the vote|first=Charlotte|last=Spratt|coauthors=Richard Simpson|work=[[The Daily Mail]]|publisher=[[Daily Mail and General Trust]]|date=December 14, 2009|accessdate=December 14, 2009|location=London}}</ref> McElderry said that the lyrics to "The Climb" meant a lot to him: "It's an emotional song because it's what's been happening in the last few months. It all feels very, very surreal."<ref name="dailymail" /> According to Peter Robinson of ''[[The Guardian]]'', the cover has a "plinky" [[piano]] in its [[introduction (music)|introduction]]. In regards to lyrics, Robinson interpreted, "lines about 'uphill battles' and 'having to lose' do seem to talk of Joe's probable future."<ref name="guardianreview">{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/musicblog/2009/dec/14/joe-mcelderry-the-climb-x-factor|work=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian Media Group|accessdate=March 30, 2010|title=Does The Climb lack the X Factor?|date=December 14, 2009|first=Peter|last=Robinson|location=London}}</ref>

=== Reception ===
Peter Robinson of ''[[The Guardian]]'' described "The Climb" as a "controversially uncontroversial choice" for a cover and continued, "While 'The Climb' might be a suitable choice for a winner's single, the fact that it's a cover of such a recent song means that it's still slightly odd."<ref name="guardianreview" />

On the week ending 26 December 2009, "The Climb" debuted at number two on the [[UK Singles Chart]]; its debut position was influenced by a [[Killing in the Name#2009 Christmas Number One campaign|campaign]] composed of [[Facebook]] group members, aimed at getting [[Rage Against the Machine]]'s "[[Killing in the Name]]" (1992) to the top position during Christmas week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/266349/rage-against-the-machine-beats-x-factor-to-uk-xmas-no-1|title=Rage Against The Machine Beats 'X Factor' To U.K. Xmas No. 1|first=Paul|last=Sexton|date=December 21, 2009|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc|accessdate=March 30, 2010}}</ref> In the following week, the song reached number one, becoming the final number one of the 2000s decade, where it maintained for a week.<ref name="ukelderry">{{cite web|url=http://www.chartstats.com/songinfo.php?id=34691|title=Chart Stats <U+2013> Joe McElderry <U+2013> The Climb|work=ChartStats.com|publisher=The Official Charts Company|accessdate=March 30, 2010}}</ref> The single was [[List of music recording sales certifications|certified platinum]] by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] (BPI) for shipments exceeding 600,000 copies.<ref name="bpi">{{cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx|title=BPI <U+2013> Certified Awards Search|work=BPI.co.uk|publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]]|accessdate=January 2, 2010}}</ref>  The song has sold 807,000 copies in the UK as of December 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-top-10-biggest-selling-x-factor-debut-singles-and-albums-revealed-1746/ |title=The Top 10 biggest selling X Factor debut singles and albums revealed! |last=Lane|first=Dan|date=20 December 2012|publisher=[[The Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=27 December 2012}}</ref>

"The Climb" debuted at number one on the [[Irish Singles Chart]] on the week ending December 17, 2009, where it maintained in the top position for four consecutive weeks.<ref name="irishsingles">{{cite web|url=http://irish-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Joe+McElderry|title=Discography Joe McElderry|work=''Irish-charts.com''|publisher=[[Irish Recorded Music Association]]|accessdate=March 30, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://acharts.us/song/52590|title=Joe McElderry <U+2013> The Climb <U+2013> Music Charts|publisher=aCharts.us|accessdate=March 30, 2009}}</ref> In mainland Europe, the song charted in the [[Eurochart Hot 100 Singles]] at number four on the week ending January 9, 2010.<ref name="europeanhot100">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/charts/european-hot-100?chartDate=2010-01-09|title=European Hot 100 <U+2013> Week of January 9, 2010|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc|accessdate=March 30, 2010|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080822150806/http://www.billboard.com/#/charts/european-hot-100?chartDate=2010-01-09|archivedate=August 22, 2008}}</ref>

=== Music video ===
[[File:Joe McElderry - The Climb music video.JPG|thumb|left|220px|McElderry performing in a flooded cityscape in "The Climb" music video]]
The video was shot on 16 December 2009, in [[London, England]].<ref name="joemusicvideo">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-1235820/X-Factor-winner-Joe-McElderry-shoots-video-single-The-Climb-keeps-fingers-crossed-Christmas-No-1.html|title=X Factor winner Joe McElderry shoots video for his single The Climb as he keeps fingers crossed for Christmas No.1|date=15 December 2009|publisher=Daily Mail and General Trust|work=Daily Mail|accessdate=December 15, 2009|location=London}}</ref> The video begins with footage from ''The X Factor'' and then transitions to a [[close-up]] shot of McElderry in the main setting, a flooded cityscape <U+2014> the scene was shot in a flooded set with a cityscape [[Theatrical scenery|backdrop]].<ref name="joemusicvideo" /> McElderry is clothed by a grey vest and a grey shirt, as he stands in the setting and performs. Throughout the entire video, scenes alternate between the flooded cityscape setting and recycled footage from ''The X Factor'', which are in black and white until it shows him in the live shows in colour. The video concludes with McElderry being informed he won the competition, hugging his peers.
{{clear}}

